    Introduction¶

    In this project, I will explore the Ford GoBike System dataset provided by Udacity. This dataset contains information about rides in Ford's bike-sharing program in the San Francisco Bay Area. This dataset's bike_share_for_all_trip column refers to a discounted GoBike membership for eligible riders of low-income.

    In the following sections, I will explore this dataset and transform it into a usable form that's suitable for analysis. I will perform univariate, bivariate, and multivariate exploration analyses to gather notable findings and guide my explanatory data analysis. Towards the end of this project, I will divulge my key insights and the significance of each insight in order to emphasize a call to action.

    What is the structure of your dataset?¶

    There are 183,412 entries and 16 columns in this dataframe.

    What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

    After carefully looking over the dataframe, I've decided to focus on users' characteristics (user_type, gender, age, bike_share_for_all status) and how ride distribution and duration change with different features (days, stations, user type, gender, age). After I explore the trends and relationships of these variables, I will convey my key insights in my explanatory data analysis.

    What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

    Overall, features that will support my investigation are user characteristics and ride distribution and duration trends. The questions I want to address in my explanatory data analysis are:

    • What trends do we see among the general Ford BikeShare user population?
    • What are the top start stations?
    • When do top stations thrive?
    • How does duration among the top stations look on different days?

    In [20]:
    #Creates a new column called "start_time_of_day" that specifies the time of day based on each start_hour
timesOfDay = []
"""
Loop that uses if and elif statements to check the value of `start_hour` and assigns it a value for the new column `start_time_of_day`
depending on the `start_hour` value (Hour that the ride starts at) 
11PM-4AM Latenight
5AM-11AM Morning
12PM-5PM Afternoon
6-10PM Night
"""
for time in df_subset['start_hour'].iloc[:]:
    #11PM-4AM latenight 
    if time <5 or time >= 23:
        timesOfDay.append("Late Night")
    #5AM-11AM morning
    elif time <12:
        timesOfDay.append("Morning")
    #12PM-5PM afternoon
    elif time < 18:
        timesOfDay.append("Afternoon")
    #6PM-10PM night
    elif time <23:
        timesOfDay.append("Night")
df_subset['start_time_of_day'] = timesOfDay

    From the graph, we can see that most users in Ford's GoBike system are around 23-40 years old.

    This graph presents a unimodal histogram with a right-skewed distribution. The duration_sec variable hits a peak in the 200-500 range. Most trips appear to be less than 800 seconds, with trips that are 1000 seconds or more being significantly less popular than those under 800 seconds. I presumed that most people would use a BikeShare service to transport themselves from point A to point B regularly, so a high amount of shorter trips makes sense.

    The graphs above display how many rides occured at a specific time of day for the top 7 start_station_names.

    Most bike rides that begin at one of the top 7 stations occur in the morning (5AM-11AM) and the least bike rides occur late at night (11PM-4AM). The majority of bike rides at these stations occur in the morning or the afternoon (77.72%). This result is unsurprising. I expected most BikeShare users to use the bikes go to work, school, or events during the day.

    Duration Distribution by Day and Gender¶

    In [43]:
    #Facet histogram on duration count by day and gender

    All visualizations are unimodal with a rightward skew. Thursday saw the highest amount of rides from males and females. The weekend had the lowest amount of rides from all genders. As expected, there are a higher amount of rides with a shorter duration than those with a longer duration.

    A previous boxplot showed that the weekend has a higher ride duration on average. However, this isn't particularly evident in this histogram. I suspect that it is because there are less rides on the weekend. A lower amount of rides may have skewed the duration average to appear higher than other days with a higher amount of rides.

    Summary¶

    I found many interesting features in the dataset. I was surprised that almost 75% of users in the dataset are males. Prior to conducting my analysis, I the ride distribution between genders would be more equal and not so disproportionate. I was unsurprised to see that most users were around 23-40 years old considering young people tend to do more physical activities. San Francisco is known for its hills so I speculate that biking in this area can be quite the workout.

    It seems that most users use the bikes to go from point A to point B. My analysis revealed that most trips are less than 800 seconds (13.33 minutes). This is understandable. I suspect that a lot of users utilize this bikeshare service to travel to and from work or school. I noticed that the stations that fared the most rides are areas that are popular for transportation or for tourists. My analysis also revealed that bike rides at top stations are more popular in the morning and in the afternoon.

    Knowing which stations are the most popular on a given day or time is beneficial in order to allow the company to better prepare for demand and increase revenue. I would have enjoyed investigating how ride duration and distribution differs by month and season. Unfortunately, this dataset only contains information for February and March of 2019. Nonetheless, I enjoyed going through the data and drawing insights. I found this dataset to be especially interesting because I was born and raised in the Bay Area.
